- Pods are rarely configured to communicate with each other directly

- If a pod should be able to access services on another pod, it would use a service

- When a service is created, it is accessible from all pods on the cluster regardless of what nodes the pods are on

- While a pod is hosted on a node, a service is hosted across a cluster and is not bound to a specific node

- REMEMBER: A service that is only accessible from within the cluster is known as ClusterIP

- REMEMBER: If a service needs to be accessible outside of the cluster, a NodePort service is created

- With a NodePort service, in addition to it getting an IP address that the pods can interact with (like any other service), it also exposes a port on all nodes in the cluster; this way, external users or applications can access this service

- The focus of this section answers the questions:
	- How are the services getting these IP addresses
	- How are the service IP addresses made available across all of the nodes in the cluster
	- How are the services made available to external users through a port on each node
	- Who is doing these things and how/where can we see it

### Process (example)

- Starting with a blank 3 node cluster, we know that every Kubernetes node runs a kubelet process, which is responsible for creating the pods

![[service-networking-1.png]]

- Each kubelet service watches for changes in the cluster through the kube-apiserver and every time a new pod is instructed to be created, kubelet creates the pod on a node
	- Kubelet, then, invokes the CNI plugin to configure networking for that pod

![[service-networking-2.png]]

- Similarly, each node runs a process known as kube-proxy

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Kube-proxy watches for changes through the kube-apiserver and every time a new service is to be created, kube-proxy goes to work; and unlike pods, services are not created on each node and are instead a cluster-wide concept

![[service-networking-4.png]]

- As we have seen, pods have containers and containers have namespaces with interfaces that have IP addresses assigned to them. But with services, nothing like this exists
	- There are no processes, namespaces or interfaces for services

- A service is just a virtual object

- If a service is just a virtual object, then how does it get an IP address and how are they accessible to pods?

- When a service is created in Kubernetes, it is assigned an IP address from a predefined range

- The kube-proxy components running on each node gets the service's IP address and creates forwarding rules on each node in the cluster which states that any traffic coming to the IP of the service should go to the IP of the pod

![[service-networking-5.png]]

- Once the service's IP forwarding is in place, whenever a pod tries to reach the IP of a service, it is forwarded to the destination pod's IP which is accessible from any node in the cluster
	- Remember, it is not just an IP, it is an IP and port combination

![[service-networking-6.png]]

- Whenever a service is created or deleted, kube-proxy creates or deletes the forwarding rules

- Kube-proxy can create forwarding rules in many different ways but the default (and most common) is by using IPTABLES rules

![[service-networking-7.png]]

- The proxy mode can be set using the `--proxy-mode` option when configuring the kube-proxy service and if this is not set, it will default to IPTABLES

![[service-networking-8.png]]

- When a service is created and an IP address is assigned to it, the option in the kube-apiserver called '--service-cluster-ip-range' is set
	- By default, this is set to 10.0.0.0/24

![[service-networking-9.png]]

- You can see what it is set to by running `ps aux | grep kube-api-server`

![[service-networking-10.png]]

- The IP address ranges specified for each network (i.e. pod, service, etc) should not overlap
	- When pod networking is setup, a CIDR range is provided which means all pod IP addresses will fall within that range. This range should not be the same as the service range

- The rules created by the kube-proxy can be seen in the IPTABLES NAT table output
	- You can search for the name of the service as all rules created by kube-proxy have a comment with the name of the service on it

![[service-networking-11.png]]

	- This is done by adding a DNAT rule to IPTABLES

![[service-networking-12.png]]
